<br>
Take the words out, leave the words in, I don't care, I just don't see what all the fuss is about.  And I don't understand why one would merit so much attention (the pledge) while the other doesn't (the almighty dollar).  If people were really this serious about it, why don't you stop using cash?  Put your credit card or your checkbook where your mouth is.  It's all or nothing.  One of the uses of the word God can't be ok and the other not ok.  You can argue until you are blue in the face about how the words in the pledge matter and how the words on our currency don't, but you are wrong.<br>
<br>
I'm sorry for my tone, but most people aren't even arguing if it's purely unconstitutional or not.  For government employees to require people to pledge their allegiance to one nation under God is unconstitutional.  It's as simple as that.  The words never bothered me and frankly, I don't see why they would be that big a deal to anyone else, other than those who have to have something to feel oppressed about.<br>
<br>
I'll tell you one thing this has done.  Everywhere I go now, I see the words &quot;One Nation Under God&quot;.  From signs in peoples' yards, to signs in stores to marquees on churches.  What was once two words in a grammar school daily ritual that no one thought about (I mean come on, no one said anything in the last 50 years, why now?) is now plastered everywhere you go.  Nice going.  Now those with a problem with those two words have much, MUCH more to contend with. <p>"I will take love wherever I find it and offer it to everyone who will take it, seek knowledge from those wiser, and teach those who wish to learn from me" - Duane Allman</p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#666666><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title><A HREF="http://www.ezboard.com/promotions/csc.html" TARGET="_blank" ><IMG SRC="http://www.ezboard.com/image/cscicon3.gif" WIDTH="20" HEIGHT="20" BORDER="0" align="absmiddle"></A> <A HREF=http://pub4.ezboard.com/uceldor.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Celdor</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Veteran</span><br>  Posts: 1995<br> <font color=#E9D756>(7/3/02 3:54:51 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub4.ezboard.com/femarrdragonsandplanes.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=3442.topic&index=244>Reply</a>    <br>ezSupporter<br> </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Carathos</span><hr size=1> What I would really like to know is how much money has been wasted on this stupid issue that could have been spent to improve our schools in a way that actually matters. Do I really care if some kid has to or doesn't have to say &quot;under God&quot;? Not really, because as a Realist, I know that its far more important that the child actually LEARN something while at school. People who want to argue about whether some words should be on currency or in a pledge really need to examine the quality of education in this country and how this money tied up in litigation could be used to better that level of learning